Session 5¶

To start this week off, you're going to take a crack at the same classification from last week but with two different algorithms. Instead of LDA, you'll be using the K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) and Support Vector Classification (SVC) algorithms to classify which species a given flower belongs to, depending on some features. A crucial part in data science is understanding how well your model performs by quantifying model performance and uncertainty. You will implement - from scratch - the bootstrapping re-sampling method. Then, you'll learn how to perform cross-validation with sklearn's model_selection.KFold.

After this session, you will be able to:

  • use sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier for general classification tasks and know how to find the optimal # of neighbors
  • use sklearn.svm.SVC for general classification tasks and know how to use different kernels
  • explain how bootstrapping & cross-validation work and what they are used for
  • use bootstrapping & cross-validation to quantify model uncertainty and performance

keywords: classifiers: K-Nearest Neighbour (KNN), Support Vector Machines — resampling methods: cross-validation, bootstrapping

K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) classifier¶

KNN is supervised machine learning algorithm that can be used for classification (data with discerete labels) or regression (data with continous labels). The basic principle behind the KNN classifier is very intituive: for a given point, find a pre-defined (k) number of training samples that are closest to that point, and predict the label from these.

We'll start off by loading the iris dataset just like last week and re-viewing how you can use seaborn to create a pairplot.

In [2]:
iris = datasets.load_iris() 
df = pd.DataFrame(iris.data)
cols = [name for name in iris.feature_names]
df.columns = cols
df['species'] = iris.target
g = sns.pairplot(df, vars=cols, hue='species', palette='colorblind')

Click me if you need help with how to use the neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier:

* Create the predictor object with the default value for number of neighbours: knn = neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5) * This creates an object (here called *knn*) that has various methods. Note how you did not give it any data yet, just model parameters. * Fit the model with your data by calling the fit method: *knn.fit(X, y)*, where *X* are the features and *y* the target. * Predict using the model with *knn.predict(X)* * You can access the mean accuracy of the fit with the *knn.score(X, y)* method

As a reminder, here's how to create a scatter plot of x1 vs x2 that colors the dots according to some third value y:

plt.scatter(x1, x2, c=y, marker='o')

where you can replace the marker paramater 'o' with, for example, 'x'.

Support Vector Machines¶

Support Vector machines (SVMs) are supvervised learning methods that can be used for classification, regression and outliers detection. A major advantage of SVMs is that they can be very effective in high-dimensional spaces. SVM work by constructing a hyper-plane or a set of hyper-planes in a high (or infinite) dimensional space that can be used for these tasks. The general idea behind SVMs is that a good separation is achieved by the hyper-plane if it has the largest possible distance to the nearest training data points.

For the next exercise, you're going to repeat the classification task from above, but this time you're going to use a support vector classification algorithm.

# to-do: use the decision_boundary function to plot
# the decision boundaries for KNN and SVC
def decision_boundary(X, y, classifier):
    """ Plots decision boundaries given input features
    X, input target y and a classifier.

    Args:
        X: features
        y: target 
        classifier: sklearn KNeighborsClassifier or SVC object
    """
    if not isinstance(X, np.ndarray):
        X = np.asarray(X)
    if not (isinstance(classifier, svm._classes.SVC)
            or isinstance(classifier, neighbors._classification.KNeighborsClassifier)):
        print('classifier needs to be a SVC or KNN object')
        return

    h = 0.05
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                         np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
    Z = classifier.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8, 6))
    ax.contourf(xx, yy, Z, alpha=0.4)
    ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y,
               edgecolor='k', s=30)
    fig.tight_layout()
    print('Mean accuracy: {:.2f}'.format(classifier.score(X, y)))

plt.figure()
decision_boundary(X, y, svc)
decision_boundary(X, y, knn)
plt.show()

Mean accuracy: 0.82

Cross-Validation and Bootstrapping¶

Resampling methods are a crucial tool to assess the performance of a model. Today, we're going to take a closer look at the boostrapping and cross-validation methods.

Bootstrapping¶

Bootstrapping allows you to create 'new' data sets from old ones, with the goal of quantifying the model uncertainty. This is done by creating a new data set by randomly sampling the 'real' data. Note that it's allowed to sample the same data points several times. You're going to build your own bootstrapping code by using the iris dataset and the KNN classifier. Start by creating a dataframe out of the iris data. Alternatively, you can also do this by working with numpy arrays.

In [84]:

df.columns = cols
df['species'] = iris.target

One way to generate a bootstrapped sample is to randomly select rows from your data by index. First, get the number of observations so we know how big our bootstrapped sample should be.

In [86]:
nobs = len(df['species'])  # number of observations

Then we create a 1d array of integers randomly picked from the interval [0, nobs] with a size of nobs. In other words, this will be a vector with nobs entries.

With these integers acting as indices you can create your boostrapped sample, fit & evaluate the model:

In [89]:
X = df[['sepal length (cm)', 'sepal width (cm)']].to_numpy()
y = df['species'].to_numpy()

df_sample = df.iloc[sample]
X_sample = df_sample[['sepal length (cm)', 'sepal width (cm)']].to_numpy()
y_sample = df_sample['species'].to_numpy()

knn = neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(1, weights='uniform')
knn.fit(X_sample, y_sample)
score = knn.score(X, y)
print('Mean accuracy: {:.2f}'.format(score))

Mean accuracy: 0.87

Let's pause here for a second:¶

In general, one should never assess the model on the same data or parts of the data that were used to train the model. But that's exactly what we're doing here. Obviously, our bootstrapped sample (X_sample, y_sample) is included in the full data (X, y).

In the future, you should always make sure to split your data into test and training sets. Let's amend the code from above to be up to that standard. Create an array of those indices that are NOT included in our bootstrapped sample.

In [90]:
# create an array of the indices that aren't included in sample
idcs = np.arange(0, y.size)
out_of_bag = np.array([i for i in idcs if i not in sample])
out_of_bag

print('Mean accuracy: {:.2f}'.format(score))

Cross-Validation¶

Recall that cross-validation is used to assess the effectiveness of a model. The idea is to separate the (randomly selected) validation set from the training set. One way to do this is to use the k-fold cross validation method, where the data is randomly divded into k groups (folds) of about equal size. The splitting of the data into training and test sets is a critical tool for machine learning.

# to-do: loop over the test/train indices and store the test scores in a list
knn = neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5, weights="uniform")
scores = np.zeros(n)
i = 0

for tr_idx, ts_idx in kf.split(X):
    Xtr, Xts = X[tr_idx], X[ts_idx]
    ytr, yts = y[tr_idx], y[ts_idx]

    knn.fit(Xtr, ytr)
    scores[i] = knn.score(Xts, yts)
